-- Japan, China, India, Malaysia, South Korea: Asian Bond, Currency Preview
-- Anil Varma
-- 2010-06-30T22:07:59Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-06-30/japan-china-india-malaysia-south-korea-asian-bond-currency-preview.html

          
          
             The following events and economic
reports may influence trading in Asia’s local bonds and
currencies today. Bond yields and exchange rates are from the
previous trading session unless stated otherwise.  
 Financial markets are shut today in Hong Kong, Pakistan and
Thailand.  
 Japan: Chief Cabinet Secretary  Yoshito Sengoku  will hold a
media briefing at 4 p.m. in Tokyo.  
 The Bank of Japan will release at 8:50 a.m. its Tankan
survey of business sentiment for the second quarter. An index of
sentiment at large manufacturers will rise 10 points to minus 4
in June, the highest level since September 2008, according to a
Bloomberg News survey of economists. A negative number means
pessimists outnumber optimists.  
 The Ministry of Finance will publish at 8:50 a.m. its
report on foreign and Japanese investment flows for domestic and
overseas securities during the week ended June 25. The ministry
will also announce the amount of 30-year Japanese government
bonds it plans to sell on July 8.  
 The yield on the 1.3 percent government bond due June 2020
was 1.085 percent, according to Japan Bond Trading Co., the
nation’s largest interdealer debt broker.  
 The yen traded at 88.39 per dollar at 7:02 a.m. in Tokyo.  
 China: The Federation of Logistics and Purchasing will say
the Purchasing Managers’ Index fell to 53.2 in June from 53.9
the previous month, according to the median forecast of
economists surveyed by Bloomberg before the data is released
today.  
 The yield on the 3.25 percent bond due in May 2020 was 3.29
percent, according to data compiled by Bloomberg. The yuan was
at 6.7814 per dollar.  
 India: The commerce ministry will report food inflation for
the week ended June 19. An index measuring wholesale prices of
agricultural products including lentils, rice and vegetables
rose 16.9 percent in the previous week from a year earlier.  
 The yield on the 7.80 percent bond due May 2020 was 7.55
percent. The rupee was at 46.46.  
 Malaysia: The government plans to sell 80 million ringgit
($25 million) of 91-day bills and 110 million ringgit of 364-day
securities.  
 The yield on the 4.378 percent debt maturing in November
2019 was 3.91 percent, according to Bursa Malaysia. The ringgit
was at 3.2320.  
 South Korea: A government report may show inflation
accelerated for a third month. The consumer price index
increased 2.9 percent in June from a year earlier, quickening
from 2.7 percent in May, according to a Bloomberg News survey.
Exports probably grew 25 percent in June from a year earlier,
after climbing 42 percent the previous month, according to a
separate survey before a government report also due today.  
 The yield on the 4.50 percent bond due in March 2015 was
4.44 percent. The won was at 1,231.20.  
